1
00:00:04,965 --> 00:00:08,389
Good afternoon, GDC.

2
00:00:08,389 --> 00:00:10,971
GDC 2010, all right!

3
00:00:10,971 --> 00:00:12,372
Best GDC ever.

4
00:00:12,372 --> 00:00:20,540
Good afternoon, and welcome to Among Friends, an Uncharted 2

5
00:00:20,540 --> 00:00:22,762
Among Thieves post-mortem.

6
00:00:22,762 --> 00:00:28,647
Please set your mobile devices to mute, and don't forget to

7
00:00:28,647 --> 00:00:30,689
fill out your feedback forms at the end of the session.

8
00:00:30,689 --> 00:00:31,390
Thanks.

9
00:00:32,391 --> 00:00:36,556
My name is Richard Lemarchand and I'm a game designer at Naughty Dog.

10
00:00:36,556 --> 00:00:42,181
I was the co-lead designer of Uncharted 2 Among Thieves

11
00:00:42,181 --> 00:00:48,128
and today I'm going to talk you through how we went about developing our game,

12
00:00:48,128 --> 00:00:52,973
what went right, and what blew up in our faces like a red explosive barrel.

13
00:00:55,610 --> 00:01:05,816
As you might know, Naughty Dog, our studio, is the creator of the multi-million selling Crash Bandicoot and Jak and Daxter series of games.

14
00:01:05,816 --> 00:01:11,239
We're based in Santa Monica in Southern California, and we currently have about 120 people on staff.

15
00:01:11,239 --> 00:01:22,265
In 2007, we released Uncharted Drake's Fortune, our first game for the PlayStation 3, which introduced the world to the adventurous fortune hunter Nathan Drake.

16
00:01:22,775 --> 00:01:26,056
And last fall we released Uncharted 2 Among Thieves,

17
00:01:26,056 --> 00:01:31,279
which has turned out to be the most successful game in our studio's history.

18
00:01:31,279 --> 00:01:36,182
Now we'd had a rough ride on Uncharted Drake's Fortune,

19
00:01:36,182 --> 00:01:41,865
including a mid-project production reset that saw us throwing away a lot of what we'd done

20
00:01:41,865 --> 00:01:46,127
and starting over. We were very happy with the game that resulted,

21
00:01:46,127 --> 00:01:49,028
but with our next game we wanted to do a lot more.

22
00:01:50,994 --> 00:01:56,177
Well, we got what we wished for because Uncharted 2 was the most ambitious project we'd ever

23
00:01:56,177 --> 00:01:57,277
attempted at Naughty Dog.

24
00:01:57,277 --> 00:02:03,480
And we chose to tackle some particularly brutal challenges, both technical and design-related.

25
00:02:03,480 --> 00:02:05,441
So how did we manage not to screw it up?

26
00:02:05,441 --> 00:02:12,284
Well, there were some things that we nearly did screw up, and hopefully this post-mortem

27
00:02:12,284 --> 00:02:17,606
will help you to avoid at least some of the spiky-ceilinged pit traps that we fell into.

28
00:02:21,362 --> 00:02:27,187
So we start every new project with a short list of project goals and we refer back to

29
00:02:27,187 --> 00:02:30,410
them throughout development to make sure that we're staying on track.

30
00:02:30,410 --> 00:02:35,714
As we completed Uncharted Drake's Fortune, we already knew that we wanted to make a sequel

31
00:02:35,714 --> 00:02:38,037
and we began to discuss what we wanted to do with it.

32
00:02:39,907 --> 00:02:44,190
Our top line goal was that we really wanted to create something that a lot of us at the

33
00:02:44,190 --> 00:02:46,732
studio had been dreaming about for a really long time.

34
00:02:46,732 --> 00:02:53,237
That is to say a fully playable version of a big summer blockbuster action-adventure

35
00:02:53,237 --> 00:02:59,522
movie which kept the player in moment-to-moment control nearly all the time as the drama exploded

36
00:02:59,522 --> 00:03:00,202
around them.

37
00:03:02,817 --> 00:03:07,680
When we were making Uncharted Drake's Fortune, we'd gone back to the roots of adventure romance

38
00:03:07,680 --> 00:03:12,843
and pulp fiction for our inspiration, kind of giving them a contemporary spin.

39
00:03:12,843 --> 00:03:17,566
Well, this time out, we wanted to stick to the same guiding principles for the world of Uncharted

40
00:03:17,566 --> 00:03:23,329
in terms of creating a colorful adventure that didn't take itself too seriously,

41
00:03:23,329 --> 00:03:26,451
but we also wanted to outdo ourselves in every way that we could think of.

42
00:03:28,191 --> 00:03:32,754
Our story in Uncharted is character-driven rather than plot-driven,

43
00:03:32,754 --> 00:03:36,837
and we decided to include a larger cast of characters in Uncharted 2.

44
00:03:36,837 --> 00:03:43,021
The other characters would help us to show more of the world that Nate operates in,

45
00:03:43,021 --> 00:03:45,663
and would act kind of like emotional satellites,

46
00:03:45,663 --> 00:03:49,806
revealing more about both the good and the darker sides of Nate's character.

47
00:03:52,727 --> 00:03:56,370
So going through the process of discussing the goals of the project

48
00:03:56,370 --> 00:04:01,314
led us to decide what Uncharted 2 would be about.

49
00:04:01,314 --> 00:04:06,899
While Uncharted Drake's fortune had greed and its consequences as its theme,

50
00:04:06,899 --> 00:04:10,422
Uncharted 2 Among Thieves would be about trust and betrayal

51
00:04:10,422 --> 00:04:14,325
and whether it's better to stay loyal to your friends

52
00:04:14,325 --> 00:04:16,087
or to act out of self-interest.

53
00:04:18,466 --> 00:04:22,968
We were going to improve and add to the gameplay of Uncharted, of course, in a focused way

54
00:04:22,968 --> 00:04:27,611
that would service this playable cinema feel that we wanted to capture, and which would

55
00:04:27,611 --> 00:04:32,733
drive many different technological improvements in our engine.

56
00:04:32,733 --> 00:04:37,216
We also knew that there were a lot of graphical improvements that we could make.

57
00:04:37,216 --> 00:04:42,459
And finally, we wanted to make an online multiplayer game using the Uncharted mechanics.

58
00:04:42,459 --> 00:04:47,741
We knew that, at the very least, we wanted to make a competitive game with several different

59
00:04:47,741 --> 00:04:48,062
game types.

60
00:04:50,395 --> 00:04:55,278
So, armed with our project goals, we set out into the pre-production phase of our project,

61
00:04:55,278 --> 00:04:59,620
which lasted for about the first six months of our 22-month development cycle.

62
00:04:59,620 --> 00:05:05,364
Pre-production is, of course, a very important phase of any game development endeavour,

63
00:05:05,364 --> 00:05:08,285
and messing it up often means messing up the whole project.

64
00:05:09,783 --> 00:05:15,069
The way that we handle pre-production at Naughty Dog is one of the things that we think makes us unusual as a studio

65
00:05:15,069 --> 00:05:21,877
in that during pre-production, we don't have anything in the way of conventional deadlines or deliverables.

66
00:05:23,917 --> 00:05:28,960
Our pre-production period is this very free form time where we conduct brainstorms, we

67
00:05:28,960 --> 00:05:33,623
talk about gameplay and story ideas, we make loads of concept art and pre-visualization

68
00:05:33,623 --> 00:05:39,527
animations and we do as much prototyping of gameplay as we can with whatever tools that

69
00:05:39,527 --> 00:05:41,648
we happen to have on hand.

70
00:05:41,648 --> 00:05:44,290
And I'll show you some of our previous animations in a few minutes.

71
00:05:44,290 --> 00:05:49,353
So by doing this we pretty quickly come up with a handful of ideas that are simply too

72
00:05:49,353 --> 00:05:51,474
good not to include in the game.

73
00:05:53,923 --> 00:05:58,425
One such idea that came to us very early was embodied in a simple photograph,

74
00:05:58,425 --> 00:06:01,347
that of the Paro Takt Stang,

75
00:06:01,347 --> 00:06:05,969
the famous Tiger's Nest Monastery in the tiny country of Bhutan,

76
00:06:05,969 --> 00:06:08,050
at the eastern end of the Himalayas.

77
00:06:08,050 --> 00:06:13,592
The way that the monastery seems to cling on to the side of the cliff

78
00:06:13,592 --> 00:06:15,373
seems perfect for Uncharted.

79
00:06:16,998 --> 00:06:21,920
So the photo gave us a good grounding in reality for the larger than life scenario that we

80
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:28,923
invented and it was also suggestive of the kind of perilous climbing gameplay that we

81
00:06:28,923 --> 00:06:29,703
love so much.

82
00:06:29,703 --> 00:06:34,546
So we soon began to design and build a level based on the tiger's nest, long before we

83
00:06:34,546 --> 00:06:38,287
had any real idea of how it fit into the rest of the game.

84
00:06:38,287 --> 00:06:41,208
And there's a cautionary tale in there which I'll tell in a moment.

85
00:06:43,587 --> 00:06:48,168
Another idea that came to us early in pre-production was the notion that Drake would fight along

86
00:06:48,168 --> 00:06:55,130
the top of a train as it sped through a landscape. The idea was such a perfect fit with the pulp-inspired

87
00:06:55,130 --> 00:07:00,271
tone of Uncharted that we knew that we had to do it, and this piece of concept art illustrated

88
00:07:00,271 --> 00:07:06,653
the idea for us just perfectly. However, we didn't want to go the same route that train

89
00:07:06,653 --> 00:07:10,014
levels in video games had taken in the past.

90
00:07:10,415 --> 00:07:15,639
where the train is actually static and the background is scrolling by creating the illusion

91
00:07:15,639 --> 00:07:22,124
of movement. We wanted to do it for real and that gives me a chance to describe how gameplay

92
00:07:22,124 --> 00:07:27,429
ideas like these in pre-production can drive the technology path that we take. So the desire

93
00:07:27,429 --> 00:07:33,494
to create this level, which was one of the first that we conceived and one of the last

94
00:07:33,494 --> 00:07:38,178
that we completed, drove an enormous chunk of the new technology we created for Uncharted 2.

95
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:42,682
technology that became very important for the cinematic set pieces

96
00:07:42,682 --> 00:07:49,865
throughout the whole game. We called it our dynamic objects traversal system.

97
00:07:49,865 --> 00:07:52,246
Anyone? Anyone?

98
00:07:52,246 --> 00:07:56,248
This system provided us with the ability to have

99
00:07:56,248 --> 00:08:01,511
player character Nathan Drake and all of his allies and enemies in the game

100
00:08:01,511 --> 00:08:04,713
able to use all of their traversal and combat abilities

101
00:08:04,713 --> 00:08:06,313
on any moving object.

102
00:08:07,228 --> 00:08:11,930
Now this might not seem like a big deal, but for those of us who had been working on 3D

103
00:08:11,930 --> 00:08:19,512
character action games for a while, it was pretty much the holy grail, because it would

104
00:08:19,512 --> 00:08:21,753
allow us to do things that we had only been able to dream of before.

105
00:08:21,753 --> 00:08:26,514
It was amazingly complicated to get this dynamic object traversal system to work.

106
00:08:26,514 --> 00:08:31,415
Our programmers had to touch or rewrite nearly every system in the game, from the player

107
00:08:31,415 --> 00:08:35,417
control to objects, to collision, to the enemies and allies AI.

108
00:08:36,713 --> 00:08:41,376
Once we decided to do it though, our programmers got to work on it straight away

109
00:08:41,376 --> 00:08:47,559
and they were already busy with it while we were in pre-production, finally

110
00:08:47,559 --> 00:08:48,660
finishing it partway through full production.

111
00:08:48,660 --> 00:08:53,663
Taking the leap to do something like this, as crazy as this,

112
00:08:53,663 --> 00:08:56,324
took a lot of tenacity and courage

113
00:08:56,324 --> 00:09:00,066
and we had to keep going even when it felt like an impossible task.

114
00:09:00,066 --> 00:09:02,908
But happily it paid off in countless ways.

115
00:09:03,197 --> 00:09:08,881
from the collapsing hotel to the convoy, Uncharted 2 was able to stand out from the crowd and

116
00:09:08,881 --> 00:09:12,524
wow our players with things that they'd just never seen before.

117
00:09:12,524 --> 00:09:20,932
One more idea that emerged from pre-production was that of Nate collapsing in the snow and

118
00:09:20,932 --> 00:09:26,756
being rescued by a mysterious stranger that for a long time we just called the Rescuer.

119
00:09:27,906 --> 00:09:32,148
Nate would then wake up in a peaceful Himalayan village and discover that his

120
00:09:32,148 --> 00:09:34,970
savior was a village leader named Tenzin

121
00:09:34,970 --> 00:09:37,352
and that they didn't share a common language.

122
00:09:37,352 --> 00:09:41,935
We planned that Nate would leave the village with Tenzin to explore a

123
00:09:41,935 --> 00:09:44,297
puzzling mountain cave system

124
00:09:44,297 --> 00:09:46,498
before returning to the village

125
00:09:46,498 --> 00:09:49,900
now, to a village now under attack by a very well-equipped army.

126
00:09:49,900 --> 00:09:54,684
We thought that this would create a particular sequence of emotional

127
00:09:54,684 --> 00:09:55,724
experience

128
00:09:55,724 --> 00:09:56,385
for the player.

129
00:09:56,735 --> 00:09:59,237
almost entirely through gameplay.

130
00:09:59,237 --> 00:10:03,361
And even though much of the rest of the story was still undecided, we were able

131
00:10:03,361 --> 00:10:07,886
to stick a pin in this idea and proceed, confident that it would find a home in

132
00:10:07,886 --> 00:10:08,727
the game.

133
00:10:08,727 --> 00:10:13,632
Now you can hear much more about these kinds of techniques and how we used

134
00:10:13,632 --> 00:10:18,757
gameplay and allied characters to create emotional experiences for the player

135
00:10:18,757 --> 00:10:20,859
by heading over to tomorrow's session.

136
00:10:21,657 --> 00:10:24,659
uh... creating the active cinematic experience of uncharted 2

137
00:10:24,659 --> 00:10:27,901
by our game director Bruce Straley

138
00:10:27,901 --> 00:10:32,244
and my co-lead designer Neil Druckmann. It's going to be excellent, don't miss it.

139
00:10:32,244 --> 00:10:38,289
So as our list of ideas grew, we experimented with putting them together

140
00:10:38,289 --> 00:10:39,129
in different orders

141
00:10:39,129 --> 00:10:42,532
to see what kinds of story ideas would emerge.

142
00:10:43,313 --> 00:10:48,757
We used a board full of index cards with story beats and character goals and gameplay moments

143
00:10:48,757 --> 00:10:54,281
that we could move around easily to try on different sequences of play.

144
00:10:54,281 --> 00:11:00,305
So with a lot of conversation, lots and lots of in-depth research into places and history,

145
00:11:00,305 --> 00:11:06,089
and then with a great deal of careful thought and hard analytical work, sequences of storytelling

146
00:11:06,089 --> 00:11:07,710
gameplay started to come together.

147
00:11:07,710 --> 00:11:11,253
And we soon had big chunks of the game figured out.

148
00:11:13,603 --> 00:11:18,326
Now this is how we create one of the most important documents of the project

149
00:11:18,326 --> 00:11:21,607
and the only deliverable for our pre-production period.

150
00:11:21,607 --> 00:11:25,529
It's a short spreadsheet, you can see part of it here,

151
00:11:25,529 --> 00:11:28,350
that we call our macro design.

152
00:11:28,350 --> 00:11:33,033
So the macro design is basically a list of the game's levels

153
00:11:33,033 --> 00:11:34,793
and corresponding story beats.

154
00:11:35,504 --> 00:11:38,106
It shows the locations that the game will visit,

155
00:11:38,106 --> 00:11:40,127
what play mechanics are used in each level,

156
00:11:40,127 --> 00:11:44,591
and whether they're core mechanics or special gameplay sequences

157
00:11:44,591 --> 00:11:45,992
like, say, a vehicle sequence.

158
00:11:45,992 --> 00:11:47,272
It shows the enemies that the player will encounter

159
00:11:47,272 --> 00:11:49,734
and what allies will accompany Drake on each stage of his journey.

160
00:11:49,734 --> 00:11:53,237
The macro also showed us that we would have a focus on Asia as a location for much of the story.

161
00:12:00,571 --> 00:12:03,754
that the true story of Marco Polo's lost fleet

162
00:12:03,754 --> 00:12:07,317
would provide us with our real-life historical mystery for the game

163
00:12:07,317 --> 00:12:10,760
and that the plot would hinge around an old friend of Nathan Drake's

164
00:12:10,760 --> 00:12:11,741
who would ultimately betray him.

165
00:12:11,741 --> 00:12:13,423
So the macro is something like a game design document.

166
00:12:19,473 --> 00:12:23,075
But it's a lot more concrete than any 100-page game design

167
00:12:23,075 --> 00:12:25,956
ever written at the end of pre-production, because it has

168
00:12:25,956 --> 00:12:28,477
enough of a level of abstraction that you don't

169
00:12:28,477 --> 00:12:31,798
waste time devising details that later get changed.

170
00:12:31,798 --> 00:12:37,841
The macro design for Uncharted 2 was only 70 rows long, and

171
00:12:37,841 --> 00:12:40,282
it shows the structure of the game that we shipped a full

172
00:12:40,282 --> 00:12:43,344
year and a half later, almost exactly to within 5% or 10%.

173
00:12:47,415 --> 00:12:53,977
So as we progressed through pre-production, there were a couple of other important gameplay systems that we decided to get busy with.

174
00:12:53,977 --> 00:13:00,058
There were a few gaps and spaces in the play mechanics of Uncharted Drake's Fortune.

175
00:13:00,058 --> 00:13:11,202
So for Uncharted 2, we gave Nate some new mechanics to fill things out, like brachiating on monkey bars, swinging on free ropes, and a nifty new hand-over-hand free climbing ability.

176
00:13:13,852 --> 00:13:18,061
We also wanted Nate to be able to pull out his gun and return fire to an enemy

177
00:13:18,061 --> 00:13:19,945
no matter what he was doing in the world.

178
00:13:19,945 --> 00:13:22,911
Whether he was climbing, balancing on a fallen beam,

179
00:13:22,911 --> 00:13:24,755
and even when he was in mid-air during a jump.

180
00:13:25,724 --> 00:13:31,607
It didn't take us very long to flesh out these abilities and expanding Drake's traversal gunplay like this

181
00:13:31,607 --> 00:13:35,049
was good for us when it came to devising combat scenarios

182
00:13:35,049 --> 00:13:40,532
because it meant that we could throw down some enemies in just any section of the game

183
00:13:40,532 --> 00:13:45,875
and in that way discover novel combat setups in the most unexpected traversal sequences.

184
00:13:48,702 --> 00:13:54,764
We also started work early in pre-production on improvements to our AI that let players

185
00:13:54,764 --> 00:14:00,386
choose to engage with our combat setups in an action stealth way.

186
00:14:00,386 --> 00:14:05,189
In order to let players hide out and observe the enemies and figure out how to possibly

187
00:14:05,189 --> 00:14:06,429
infiltrate their ranks.

188
00:14:06,805 --> 00:14:10,847
and even manipulate them into positions that would make them easier to defeat.

189
00:14:10,847 --> 00:14:13,809
We gave our enemies an investigate behavior

190
00:14:13,809 --> 00:14:18,451
that they would use when they thought they'd heard or seen something unusual

191
00:14:18,451 --> 00:14:20,112
and also a search behavior

192
00:14:20,112 --> 00:14:22,153
that they would use when they had seen Drake

193
00:14:22,153 --> 00:14:24,014
but they didn't currently know where he was.

194
00:14:24,014 --> 00:14:29,317
Now these techniques paid off right throughout the whole player experience

195
00:14:29,317 --> 00:14:33,199
so it was really good that we got started on them early during pre-production.

196
00:14:36,137 --> 00:14:41,582
One last important thing for us to do during pre-production was to get a handle on how long it was going to take us

197
00:14:41,582 --> 00:14:45,445
to create the big set pieces that we wanted to have in the game.

198
00:14:45,445 --> 00:14:49,549
One particular sequence from Uncharted Drake's Fortune

199
00:14:49,549 --> 00:14:52,732
had stuck in our minds and really fired our imaginations.

200
00:14:52,732 --> 00:14:57,676
It was the one you can see here, just a simple sequence at the island waterfall

201
00:14:57,676 --> 00:15:00,619
where an explosion near a truck full of enemies

202
00:15:00,619 --> 00:15:02,400
flips the truck and forms a bridge.

203
00:15:03,377 --> 00:15:08,698
It was a really dramatic moment, just like something from one of our favorite action-adventure movies,

204
00:15:08,698 --> 00:15:12,019
but it played out almost entirely in gameplay.

205
00:15:12,019 --> 00:15:17,800
It made us feel that we had only begun to scratch the surface of what was possible

206
00:15:17,800 --> 00:15:22,321
in terms of delivering a truly interactive cinematic experience.

207
00:15:22,321 --> 00:15:28,182
And we thought that making bigger set pieces and moving away from so-called quick-time events

208
00:15:28,182 --> 00:15:29,603
was probably a great way to go.

209
00:15:31,878 --> 00:15:38,642
Well, it was a great way to go, and everyone seems to really like the set pieces in Uncharted 2.

210
00:15:38,642 --> 00:15:42,364
However, they are enormously time-consuming to implement.

211
00:15:42,364 --> 00:15:53,189
We had foreseen this, and so early on in pre-production, we got busy building a version of the collapsing bridge in the monastery that you encounter towards the end of the game.

212
00:15:53,189 --> 00:15:58,732
We confirmed our suspicions about how extremely time-consuming that kind of sequence was to build.

213
00:15:59,429 --> 00:16:02,071
and so we hired some very technical scripting designers

214
00:16:02,071 --> 00:16:07,534
trying to make sure that we had enough people to get everything done in time.

215
00:16:07,534 --> 00:16:11,457
It didn't quite work out perfectly though, as you'll hear later on.

216
00:16:11,457 --> 00:16:17,861
One of the most important things that we had taken away from our post-mortem

217
00:16:17,861 --> 00:16:20,042
of Uncharted Drake's fortune

218
00:16:20,042 --> 00:16:23,985
was that simply getting on and starting to build something

219
00:16:23,985 --> 00:16:28,107
is the very best way to go about the creation of a video game.

220
00:16:29,129 --> 00:16:35,235
We'd spent far too long theorizing about our game's design and production during the creation

221
00:16:35,235 --> 00:16:39,639
of the first Uncharted, and it wasn't until we pressed forward with the construction of

222
00:16:39,639 --> 00:16:44,323
some gameplay and levels that we made the real discoveries that allowed us to optimize

223
00:16:44,323 --> 00:16:46,105
the production and finish the game in good style.

224
00:16:46,105 --> 00:16:47,747
So we did our best to hit the ground running with Uncharted 2.

225
00:16:54,053 --> 00:16:58,315
The team was eager to keep the production momentum that we'd built up over the previous

226
00:16:58,315 --> 00:17:01,056
three years working on Uncharted Drake's Fortune.

227
00:17:01,056 --> 00:17:06,219
And using the first ideas we decided that we would use, everyone began to create art

228
00:17:06,219 --> 00:17:11,881
and implement game mechanics and layout levels almost immediately.

229
00:17:11,881 --> 00:17:16,503
Now this meant that our artists were polishing their level building approach and making useful

230
00:17:16,503 --> 00:17:19,165
assets much earlier than they'd been able to before.

231
00:17:19,705 --> 00:17:27,530
And by the time we hit full production, we were in a much better position than we had been at the same stage of the last project.

232
00:17:27,530 --> 00:17:37,997
However, moving forward so quickly meant that the end of pre-production and the beginning of full production kind of got a bit blurry.

233
00:17:37,997 --> 00:17:43,661
We came to the official end of pre-production when we finished our macro design, but it was something of a soft finish.

234
00:17:44,112 --> 00:17:47,937
The parts of the macro to do with the way that the story came together

235
00:17:47,937 --> 00:17:52,142
at the end of the game were a bit light on detail.

236
00:17:52,142 --> 00:17:55,907
And this led us directly into what could have been

237
00:17:55,907 --> 00:17:58,450
an enormous disaster for our project

238
00:17:58,450 --> 00:17:59,952
and which we only narrowly avoided.

239
00:18:02,144 --> 00:18:06,066
It took us a long time to work out how the story would come together,

240
00:18:06,066 --> 00:18:07,847
in the monastery in particular.

241
00:18:07,847 --> 00:18:11,008
And when you play it through, you might notice that there aren't really enough

242
00:18:11,008 --> 00:18:12,849
strong story beats there

243
00:18:12,849 --> 00:18:16,431
to match the length and the intensity of the gameplay.

244
00:18:16,431 --> 00:18:18,372
And it's the first place in the game

245
00:18:18,372 --> 00:18:22,054
where the pace of the experience kind of begins to lose steam a bit.

246
00:18:22,054 --> 00:18:27,337
Of course, as soon as we realized what was happening, we scrambled to patch things up.

247
00:18:27,966 --> 00:18:31,830
but at the end of the day we had committed too much to the level

248
00:18:31,830 --> 00:18:33,111
in terms of its final art

249
00:18:33,111 --> 00:18:36,675
and we couldn't really bring about a perfect fix.

250
00:18:36,675 --> 00:18:41,079
So this is the first major takeaway from this post-mortem of Uncharted 2.

251
00:18:41,079 --> 00:18:46,224
That it's important to have a strong macro design.

252
00:18:47,420 --> 00:18:52,724
If the macro is solid and describes a rising and falling rhythm of story

253
00:18:52,724 --> 00:18:55,586
that tightly matches the rhythms of the gameplay,

254
00:18:55,586 --> 00:18:59,149
then you can be confident that your game is going to rock.

255
00:18:59,149 --> 00:19:01,731
However, if your macro has any weak spots,

256
00:19:01,731 --> 00:19:07,015
do make sure you firm them up before you commit too much in the way of

257
00:19:07,015 --> 00:19:08,937
final art to that part of the game.

258
00:19:09,577 --> 00:19:13,658
and tried to pay special attention to pacing issues for parts of the game

259
00:19:13,658 --> 00:19:18,299
whose level design starts early and whose story design finishes late.

260
00:19:18,299 --> 00:19:23,521
So anyway, to round off the pre-production section of my talk, I want to show you guys

261
00:19:23,521 --> 00:19:29,603
what is a world exclusive, especially for GDC.

262
00:19:29,603 --> 00:19:35,085
While we were making Uncharted Drake's Fortune, we had learned firsthand about

263
00:19:35,085 --> 00:19:36,365
the power of

264
00:19:36,365 --> 00:19:38,746
pre-rendered, pre-visualization animations.

265
00:19:39,803 --> 00:19:45,564
By making quickly and loosely animated sequences, pre-rendered linear sequences, with blocky,

266
00:19:45,564 --> 00:19:52,306
low detailed worlds and characters, we can very quickly start to refine our ideas, the

267
00:19:52,306 --> 00:19:54,887
kinds of ideas that we've had for moments in the game.

268
00:19:54,887 --> 00:20:01,268
They're kind of like moving concept art, and we refer back to them all throughout the level

269
00:20:01,268 --> 00:20:01,728
layout process.

