00:24:53,492 --> 00:24:55,253
events in the game might play out.

313
00:24:55,253 --> 00:24:56,234
So we officially started full production

314
00:24:56,234 --> 00:24:57,194
when we finished our macro design in April 2008.

315
00:24:57,194 --> 00:25:01,116
Of course, once we were in full production,

316
00:25:01,116 --> 00:25:06,539
we needed some micro design to go along with our macro design.

317
00:25:06,539 --> 00:25:11,881
What we call micro design is all the detailed design work

318
00:25:11,881 --> 00:25:17,884
that needs to be done to create a video game, level layout,

319
00:25:17,884 --> 00:25:19,525
mechanics development, and so on.

320
00:25:20,945 --> 00:25:24,668
We do this macro design work on a just-in-time basis.

321
00:25:24,668 --> 00:25:28,672
It's a bit like Gromit laying out the toy train tracks only

322
00:25:28,672 --> 00:25:30,653
just ahead of himself in the wrong trousers.

323
00:25:30,653 --> 00:25:32,715
We had gotten a leg up with the micro design during

324
00:25:32,715 --> 00:25:35,818
pre-production, and we were just far enough ahead of the

325
00:25:35,818 --> 00:25:38,560
team that we were able to move forward smoothly.

326
00:25:38,560 --> 00:25:43,965
Even though this part of the way that we work might seem

327
00:25:43,965 --> 00:25:46,067
like a pretty seat-of-the-pants way to do

328
00:25:46,067 --> 00:25:46,427
things.

329
00:25:46,767 --> 00:25:51,309
We think that it's the way that a lot of game development happens in truth,

330
00:25:51,309 --> 00:25:55,172
and that we just have the courage to make it an official part of our process.

331
00:25:55,172 --> 00:26:00,335
One very important and time-consuming part of the micro-design is level layout, of course.

332
00:26:00,335 --> 00:26:08,801
Inspired by our philosophy that getting on and building out the game is the best way to go about things,

333
00:26:08,801 --> 00:26:11,863
we adopted a new level layout approach for Uncharted 2.

334
00:26:12,613 --> 00:26:17,254
that saw us spending less time working on detailed paper maps of our levels

335
00:26:17,254 --> 00:26:22,656
and instead designing our levels by creating what we refer to as block mesh

336
00:26:22,656 --> 00:26:25,297
which some studios refer to as white box or grey box.

337
00:26:25,297 --> 00:26:29,199
We started by sketching out an experiential flow for the player

338
00:26:29,199 --> 00:26:34,320
and then meeting with the artists and the programmers who would be working on the level with the designers

339
00:26:34,320 --> 00:26:36,121
to get their input and their ideas.

340
00:26:37,476 --> 00:26:43,158
Then we just started building a simple geometry in Maya to rough out a physical footprint

341
00:26:43,158 --> 00:26:48,719
for the level and playtesting it on literally anyone who came within arm's reach and getting

342
00:26:48,719 --> 00:26:51,860
constructive input from as many different people as possible.

343
00:26:51,860 --> 00:26:58,343
We started to do paint-overs with our concept artists to move our conception of the look

344
00:26:58,343 --> 00:26:59,163
of the level along.

345
00:27:00,097 --> 00:27:05,201
And after that, it was simply a question of iterating as much and as quickly as we could

346
00:27:05,201 --> 00:27:10,584
before we needed to hand off the block mesh to our environment artists, who would continue

347
00:27:10,584 --> 00:27:17,388
to iterate on the level by making progressive detail passes until we eventually arrive at

348
00:27:17,388 --> 00:27:18,329
the finished art.

349
00:27:18,329 --> 00:27:23,111
There is one potential downside to rushing ahead with level layout in block mesh like

350
00:27:23,111 --> 00:27:29,415
this, which is that there's a danger of not putting quite enough thought into the layout.

351
00:27:29,829 --> 00:27:33,190
and of missing some opportunities to make it multi-dimensional

352
00:27:33,190 --> 00:27:36,712
in terms of its gameplay possibilities.

353
00:27:36,712 --> 00:27:40,635
You also run the risk of not thinking about whether what you laid out as a

354
00:27:40,635 --> 00:27:45,377
blank wall will become filled with attractive detail and look climbable,

355
00:27:45,377 --> 00:27:47,118
misleading or confusing the player.

356
00:27:47,118 --> 00:27:50,880
And unfortunately this is a pretty serious problem in Uncharted 2,

357
00:27:50,880 --> 00:27:55,383
especially in detail-rich areas like the one you see here.

358
00:27:56,417 --> 00:28:00,299
So in the future, we're going to try and find a better balance

359
00:28:00,299 --> 00:28:04,121
as regards these aspects of our layout process.

360
00:28:04,121 --> 00:28:08,543
And we're going to try and have more of a layout focus

361
00:28:08,543 --> 00:28:10,404
on realistic architecture earlier

362
00:28:10,404 --> 00:28:11,625
and how its details will affect the player's experience.

363
00:28:11,625 --> 00:28:15,287
In full production, our project runs

364
00:28:15,287 --> 00:28:18,168
much like a conventionally scheduled game development

365
00:28:18,168 --> 00:28:19,269
project.

366
00:28:19,269 --> 00:28:21,310
Working from the macro design, we

367
00:28:21,310 --> 00:28:24,051
drew up a simple schedule for the environment art

368
00:28:24,051 --> 00:28:25,292
in a spreadsheet.

369
00:28:25,662 --> 00:28:29,683
blocking out week-long chunks of time for our environment art groups.

370
00:28:29,683 --> 00:28:34,905
We were able to do this with confidence because the macro design had given us just enough

371
00:28:34,905 --> 00:28:40,128
detail to see where our effort should be distributed, and we knew that since the creation of the

372
00:28:40,128 --> 00:28:44,730
environments was the most time-consuming thing that we had on our plates, we could use this

373
00:28:44,730 --> 00:28:49,632
main schedule as a kind of backbone of schedule for everything else to hang off, and that

374
00:28:49,632 --> 00:28:53,733
we could always be sure that we were making solid progress towards our final goal.

375
00:28:56,104 --> 00:29:02,106
As the level designs firmed up, we also got busy making lists of everything that we needed for each level,

376
00:29:02,106 --> 00:29:08,027
since we wanted to make each one as functionally complete as soon as we could.

377
00:29:08,027 --> 00:29:14,829
So we listed out objects, sound effects, visual effects, and animations that we needed to tie everything together,

378
00:29:14,829 --> 00:29:19,950
and we got them into the hands of the relevant leads as early as we could.

379
00:29:19,950 --> 00:29:24,091
We need an enormous volume of entities to make a game like Uncharted 2.

380
00:29:25,098 --> 00:29:33,222
For example, we had 80 in-game cinematic animations, what we call IGCs, in Uncharted Drake's Fortune.

381
00:29:33,222 --> 00:29:37,104
But we had 564 IGCs for Uncharted 2.

382
00:29:37,104 --> 00:29:43,988
Now, this is a pretty amazingly large amount of work to requisition and produce on an ad-hoc basis.

383
00:29:43,988 --> 00:29:48,170
So the leads of each department had to juggle their priorities a lot,

384
00:29:48,170 --> 00:29:51,692
and they worked very hard to get everything built in the right order.

385
00:29:52,808 --> 00:29:57,971
They had to be very patient as the designer of each level came up to them, bugging them

386
00:29:57,971 --> 00:30:01,132
over and over again for the stuff that they needed.

387
00:30:01,132 --> 00:30:03,373
And it's really only because of our ability to work together without much friction that

388
00:30:03,373 --> 00:30:04,613
our games always come together on time.

389
00:30:04,613 --> 00:30:05,314
So now let's talk tech for a bit.

390
00:30:05,314 --> 00:30:08,395
We had created an entirely new engine from scratch in the course of developing the first

391
00:30:08,395 --> 00:30:08,755
Uncharted.

392
00:30:20,613 --> 00:30:23,755
And that really allowed us to hit the ground running when we started Uncharted 2.

393
00:30:23,755 --> 00:30:26,857
But we had a long laundry list of improvements and updates that we wanted to make.

394
00:30:26,857 --> 00:30:31,280
And by the time we finished, we'd changed so much that we dubbed the engine the Naughty Dog Engine 2.0.

395
00:30:31,280 --> 00:30:36,463
As you've probably heard already, if you're interested in PS3 development, we went cell processor crazy on Uncharted 2.

396
00:30:47,628 --> 00:30:53,369
We were famous for saying that Uncharted Drake's Fortune probably only used about 30% of the

397
00:30:53,369 --> 00:30:58,731
capacity of the cell processor, which is of course the powerful chip that lies at the

398
00:30:58,731 --> 00:31:00,131
heart of the PlayStation 3's architecture.

399
00:31:00,131 --> 00:31:03,552
And so from the very beginning of the project, our programs were focused on making sure that

400
00:31:03,552 --> 00:31:05,913
we squeezed every last ounce of performance out of the cell.

401
00:31:05,913 --> 00:31:10,514
The key to doing this was deciding which jobs we wanted to farm out to the cell.

402
00:31:17,210 --> 00:31:22,396
and then writing hand optimized code to do those jobs as efficiently as possible.

403
00:31:22,396 --> 00:31:27,922
And you can see just how much of what the cells' SPUs are doing

404
00:31:27,922 --> 00:31:32,407
has been diligently optimized by a cycle counting programmer

405
00:31:32,407 --> 00:31:33,188
in this screenshot.

406
00:31:35,762 --> 00:31:37,622
Probably the biggest technical change from the way

407
00:31:37,622 --> 00:31:40,122
that we did things on the first Uncharted

408
00:31:40,122 --> 00:31:43,623
was that we used the cell processor as a graphics chip,

409
00:31:43,623 --> 00:31:47,244
running it in parallel with the PS3's dedicated graphics

410
00:31:47,244 --> 00:31:49,764
processor, the RSX.

411
00:31:49,764 --> 00:31:52,985
We only did vertex processing on the SPUs before Uncharted 2,

412
00:31:52,985 --> 00:31:54,005
but now we do pixel processing.

413
00:31:54,005 --> 00:31:55,485
And we get much richer graphics by doing this.

414
00:31:55,485 --> 00:31:56,785
By moving jobs to the SPUs, we were

415
00:31:56,785 --> 00:31:57,825
free to do more on the RSX.

416
00:32:04,544 --> 00:32:08,606
and you can see the graphical leap forward that we made as a result of this

417
00:32:08,606 --> 00:32:13,349
when you look at the snow and the ice shaders that we created for the ice cave

418
00:32:13,349 --> 00:32:17,351
you can also see the fur shaders

419
00:32:17,351 --> 00:32:19,812
uh... who also made the fur shaders possible

420
00:32:19,812 --> 00:32:22,593
for our awesome howling wolves

421
00:32:22,593 --> 00:32:24,154
i so wish we could get this t-shirt

422
00:32:28,365 --> 00:32:35,430
We used light maps for the first time to get better detail in our pre-rendered shadowing in Uncharted 2.

423
00:32:35,430 --> 00:32:43,835
And to complement them, we were also able to use a lighting technique called Screen Space Ambient Occlusion, or SSAO,

424
00:32:43,835 --> 00:32:48,978
which was hugely instrumental in making our game look as solid and as grounded as it does.

425
00:32:50,292 --> 00:32:56,217
SSAO is a rendering technique for efficiently approximating the computer graphics ambient

426
00:32:56,217 --> 00:33:03,563
occlusion effect in real time and as I move through these slides hopefully you can notice

427
00:33:03,563 --> 00:33:03,803
the effect.

428
00:33:03,803 --> 00:33:10,289
Ambient occlusion is what simulates the real world effect of the darkening that you see

429
00:33:10,289 --> 00:33:16,974
in nooks and crannies and in the concave space where two convex objects touch each other

430
00:33:16,974 --> 00:33:19,116
like in between your fingers right here.

431
00:33:21,507 --> 00:33:25,350
Our SSAO is completely on the cell processor's SPUs.

432
00:33:25,350 --> 00:33:28,692
Our graphical post-processing effects were also completely on the SPUs.

433
00:33:28,692 --> 00:33:33,395
These included big improvements in the quality of our bloom effects

434
00:33:33,395 --> 00:33:39,519
and the huge leaps forward that we made with depth of field,

435
00:33:39,519 --> 00:33:42,440
which was kind of a hack for the first Uncharted,

436
00:33:42,440 --> 00:33:46,383
but which for Uncharted 2 was a much more physically correct solution.

437
00:33:46,807 --> 00:33:50,850
which of course made the times that we used it in the service

438
00:33:50,850 --> 00:33:55,174
of cinematography that much more powerful as a storytelling

439
00:33:55,174 --> 00:33:55,854
tool.

440
00:33:55,854 --> 00:33:59,498
We also implemented a filmic HDR response curve.

441
00:33:59,498 --> 00:34:02,280
And Uncharted 2 has a much wider range

442
00:34:02,280 --> 00:34:05,703
of colors in between light and dark than its predecessor,

443
00:34:05,703 --> 00:34:09,286
making it look much more like the game was shot on film,

444
00:34:09,286 --> 00:34:12,789
again, supporting our goal of creating a cinematic reality.

445
00:34:15,365 --> 00:34:17,527
So nine months before launch, we suddenly

446
00:34:17,527 --> 00:34:21,990
realized that our frame rate was, to put it bluntly,

447
00:34:21,990 --> 00:34:23,050
pretty crap.

448
00:34:23,050 --> 00:34:26,893
So we had to mobilize to fix it.

449
00:34:26,893 --> 00:34:28,694
And right up to the end of the project,

450
00:34:28,694 --> 00:34:31,536
we had a huge focus on frame rate.

451
00:34:31,536 --> 00:34:33,637
Both our programmers and our artists

452
00:34:33,637 --> 00:34:35,939
had to work very hard on the issue

453
00:34:35,939 --> 00:34:39,501
to make sure that we hit 30 frames a second consistently

454
00:34:39,501 --> 00:34:43,084
throughout the whole game, and so banish some of the issues

455
00:34:43,084 --> 00:34:44,585
with tearing and stuttering.

