00:39:37,443 --> 00:39:42,325
team deathmatches to intensely collaborative match types like Plunder, which is our take

536
00:39:42,325 --> 00:39:46,566
on Capture the Flag, where you have to get a big gold head back to a treasure chest in

537
00:39:46,566 --> 00:39:47,026
your base.

538
00:39:48,529 --> 00:39:55,795
One of our studio's co-presidents, Christoph Bollestra, wrote all of our networking code in-house from the ground up.

539
00:39:55,795 --> 00:39:59,718
He gave us a very solid base to build our multiplayer game on,

540
00:39:59,718 --> 00:40:05,803
and he was able to support us throughout the whole of development, even though he had a lot of other responsibilities.

541
00:40:07,752 --> 00:40:13,135
Rather than going with a dedicated server service, we chose to use the Amazon Elastic

542
00:40:13,135 --> 00:40:19,177
Compute Cloud, otherwise known as EC2, for things like our statistics and the machinima

543
00:40:19,177 --> 00:40:22,819
cinema files that players are able to upload to the network.

544
00:40:22,819 --> 00:40:26,661
Amazon's EC2 service is very scalable.

545
00:40:27,097 --> 00:40:31,602
Basically, you only pay for as much bandwidth as you use.

546
00:40:31,602 --> 00:40:38,530
And by choosing to use it, we have saved ourselves what will probably add up to a large fraction

547
00:40:38,530 --> 00:40:42,975
of a million dollars across the lifetime of our multiplayer game.

548
00:40:42,975 --> 00:40:44,417
So that's something to think about.

