00:42:07,505 --> 00:42:11,907
and they really rocked the huge responsibility that multiplayer implied.

565
00:42:14,204 --> 00:42:19,609
When we announced our multiplayer game at a special press event in early 2009,

566
00:42:19,609 --> 00:42:23,372
some internet posting fans of Uncharted Drake's Fortune

567
00:42:23,372 --> 00:42:27,335
were concerned that the single-player game of Uncharted 2 was going to suffer

568
00:42:27,335 --> 00:42:31,398
as a result of the attention that we would have to give our multiplayer game.

569
00:42:31,398 --> 00:42:36,562
Well, even though we did have to do a lot of hard work to realize all of our ambitions,

570
00:42:36,562 --> 00:42:41,246
it turned out that the multiplayer actually helped the single-player game.

571
00:42:41,246 --> 00:42:43,848
You see, we had to tighten up the player mechanics.

572
00:42:44,228 --> 00:42:47,769
and make them a lot snappier once we got them into a multiplayer context.

573
00:42:47,769 --> 00:42:54,351
And that actually fed back into the single player game and gave it a much better, tighter

574
00:42:54,351 --> 00:42:54,471
feel.

575
00:42:54,471 --> 00:42:57,752
These are the kinds of synergies that we love to find when we're building a game, and we're

576
00:42:57,752 --> 00:42:58,893
always on the lookout for them.

577
00:42:58,893 --> 00:43:01,093
So that was a terrific one to discover.

578
00:43:01,093 --> 00:43:04,414
During the development of Uncharted 2, we took our first steps into what was for us

579
00:43:13,557 --> 00:43:19,439
We took our first steps into the brave new world of outsourced art assets.

580
00:43:19,439 --> 00:43:25,381
We worked with Expec in Taiwan and Lady Luck in the Philippines, and both studios did a

581
00:43:25,381 --> 00:43:26,561
really amazing job.

582
00:43:26,561 --> 00:43:30,203
For our part, we made sure that we gave our partners everything they needed to succeed,

583
00:43:30,203 --> 00:43:34,324
and we almost went as far as training them to make art that we could use.

584
00:43:34,324 --> 00:43:37,025
We would provide a package of reference materials.

585
00:43:43,517 --> 00:43:47,600
that included specifications and quite detailed construction

586
00:43:47,600 --> 00:43:50,201
instructions, screenshots of the locations

587
00:43:50,201 --> 00:43:53,884
where the assets would be used to show their context,

588
00:43:53,884 --> 00:43:58,046
and prototype geometry to define precisely the volumes

589
00:43:58,046 --> 00:44:01,008
that the assets should occupy.

590
00:44:01,008 --> 00:44:03,510
We ended up outsourcing all sorts of work

591
00:44:03,510 --> 00:44:06,071
from environments and cut scene stages

592
00:44:06,071 --> 00:44:10,414
to characters and accessories, along with monotonous work

593
00:44:10,414 --> 00:44:12,195
like UVing and LODing.

594
00:44:12,754 --> 00:44:19,319
And it's really thanks to our outsourcing teams that our game is as full of eye candy as it is.

595
00:44:19,319 --> 00:44:26,664
Outsourcing in this way didn't seem to have any uncomfortable or negative effects on our company culture either.

